Speechify Inc: Software Engineer, macOS Core Product

Headquarters: Florida
    URL: http://www.speechify.com


Role Overview
As aSoftware Engineer on the macOS team, youll help build and scale Speechifys core desktop experience for millions of users. Youll own significant parts of our macOS app architecture, ship production-ready code, and collaborate closely with product, design, and engineering teams across the company.
This is a key role for someone who thrives in a fast-paced startup environment, enjoys making high-impact product decisions, loves delightful user experiences, and has a passion for accessibility and performance.
What Youll Do

Lead key engineering and product decisions for the macOS app.
Write, test, and ship production-quality code that scales to millions of users.
Maintain and evolve complex app architecture with a focus on performance and stability.
Work within a cross-functional team, partnering with designers and PMs to shape features from concept to launch.
Participate in product planning and roadmap discussions.
Drive continuous improvement in code quality, CI/CD processes, and development workflows.

You should have:

Demonstrated experience shipping macOS (or related desktop) applications used by many customers.
Strong engineering instincts with a deep focus on user experience.
A strategic mindset for building great productsnot just writing code.
Ability to work quickly, decide what to build now vs. later, and iterate fast.
Experience working in remote, distributed teams.

Technical requirements:

Swift / SwiftUI (macOS) proficiency.
Solid understanding ofAppKit, macOS frameworks, and desktop-specific UI paradigms.
Experience in multithreaded programming.
Familiarity with CI/CD workflows (e.g., Xcode Cloud, GitHub Actions).
Strong version control skills (Git), including branching strategies.

What We offer:

Impact & Ownership:Build and influence a product used by millions globally.
Remote First:Flexible, asynchronous work culture.
Growth & Leadership:Flat org  leadership is earned by impact, not title.
Collaborative Environment:Work with smart, passionate engineers and designers.
Competitive Compensation:Market-aligned salary, bonus, and equity.

Why Join Speechify?
At Speechify, we ship fast, build for real users, and care deeply about quality and accessibility. Youll work on products that change lives, and your contributions will shape both the product and the company.
If this sounds like your kind of challenge, wed love to hear from you.Apply with your resume and links to your portfolio or GitHub!
Think youre a good fit for this job?
Tell us more about yourself and why you're interested in the role when you apply.And dont forget to include links to your portfolio and LinkedIn.
Not looking but know someone who would make a great fit?
Refer them!
Speechify is committed to a diverse and inclusive workplace.
Speechify does not discriminate on the basis of race, national origin, gender, gender identity, sexual orientation, protected veteran status, disability, age, or other legally protected status.

To apply: https://weworkremotely.com/remote-jobs/speechify-inc-software-engineer-macos-core-product

EBG: PHP Web Application Developer

Headquarters: San Antonio, TX, USA
    URL: http://ebgsolutions.com


Company DescriptionEBG is an e-commerce solutions provider specializing in travel and entertainment, and also offering retail products and services, voluntary benefits and insurance.EBG powers a robust portfolio of technology solutions and operates a network of employer and membership-based platforms reaching a captive audience, providing leading brands with incremental distribution opportunities. EBG's expanded network reaches over 100 million users from participating companies and closed loop affinity and membership groups.EBG owns and operates one of the largest and most comprehensive employee savings programs in the country  serving over 40,000 corporate clients through its proprietary platforms TicketsatWork, Plum Benefits, Working Advantage and Beneplace.EBG is a b2b2c company headquartered in Miami (Aventura), with offices in New York, Orlando, and Austin. We offer a hybrid work environment with a balance of collaboration and flexibility.Job DescriptionIn this role you will embark on a large-scale, multi-year modernization initiative to transform a legacy monolithic PHP application into a modern, microservice-oriented architecture hosted on AWS. Your role as a Web Developer will bring deep experience in API-driven development, AWS cloud infrastructure, and modern DevOps practices to help drive this transformation.Youll play a key role in decoupling business domains, architecting, implementing, and maintaining new microservices using Symfony/Doctrine or similar frameworks. Your focus will be on delivering high-quality, secure, and scalable API integrations. Ideally, you bring hands-on experience across the full development lifecycle  from design and implementation to CI/CD and infrastructure-as-code  all within an Agile Scrum environment.This role is primarily WFH / Remote for Florida and Texas candidates but requires flexibility to attend any in office team meetings as needed.**You must reside in FL or TX** to be hired for this position.Key ResponsibilitiesHave strong presence in the decoupling of the existing PHP monolith into domain-driven microservices and APIs.Design, develop, and maintain back-end services using Symfony (or equivalent MVC frameworks) and Doctrine ORM.Architect and implement RESTful APIs and ensure consistent documentation, testing, and versioning practices.Build and consume third-party APIs, ensuring performance, scalability, and security best practices.Collaborate closely with DevOps and Infrastructure teams to design cloud-native solutions using AWS services (e.g., Lambda, ECS, EKS, S3, API Gateway).Containerize applications using Docker and manage orchestration via Kubernetes/ECS.Implement and maintain CI/CD pipelines to support rapid, reliable deployments.Leverage infrastructure-as-code (IaC) tools to ensure reproducible and maintainable environments.Contribute to architectural design discussions, code reviews, and cross-functional planning.Work within an Agile Scrum framework, participating in sprint grooming, planning, demo, and retrospectives.Collaborate with Product, QA, and Analytics teams to ensure feature alignment and data integrity.Qualifications3+ years of professional experience in back-end development with PHP (Symfony preferred).Strong understanding of microservice architecture and API-first design principles.Proven experience deploying and managing applications on AWS (ECS, EKS, Lambda, API Gateway, RDS, CloudWatch, etc.).Proficiency with Docker and Kubernetes (EKS or equivalent) for containerized deployments.Hands-on experience with CI/CD pipelines (e.g., GitHub Actions, Jenkins, GitLab CI, or AWS CodePipeline).Experience using Infrastructure-as-Code tools such as Terraform or AWS CloudFormation.Strong understanding of third-party API integration patterns, rate limiting, and error handling best practices.Experience working within an Agile/Scrum environment.Solid understanding of software design patterns, version control (Git), and code quality best practices.Excellent problem-solving, communication, and collaboration skills.YOU MUST RESIDE IN FL or TX*EBG does not offer sponsorship for this role.What Sets You Apart:AWS Certification (Developer Associate or Solutions Architect).Experience with Doctrine ORM, Symfony 6, or similar frameworks.Knowledge of serverless architecture patterns using AWS Lambda and API Gateway.Familiarity with event-driven architecture, message queues (e.g., SNS/SQS, Kafka), or data streaming.Background in travel, hospitality, or entertainment industries, especially with booking, ticketing, or reservation systems.Exposure to observability tools with focus on New Relic (other examples include CloudWatch, Datadog, or ELK stack).Understanding of security best practices for cloud-based microservices (IAM, least privilege, encryption).Experience mentoring developers or leading small Agile teams.Additional InformationEBG offers outstanding employee benefits including:Medical, Dental & Vision401k MatchShort Term Disability, Long Term Disability (Company Paid)Company Paid Basic Life and AD&D;Additional Voluntary BenefitsFlexible Work Arrangements3 Weeks of PTO + 5 Personal DaysPaid Holiday Break from Christmas to New YearPaid HolidaysFitness Reimbursement ProgramAnnual Day of GivingShare in the FUN! EBG gives $1000 per year in Tickets-At-Work gift cardsto full-time employees to experience and enjoy the savings marketplace!The statements contained herein reflect general details as necessary to describe the principal functions of this job, the level of knowledge and skill typically required, and the scope of responsibility, but should not be considered an all-inclusive listing of work requirements. All your information will be kept confidential according to EEO guidelines.

To apply: https://weworkremotely.com/remote-jobs/ebg-php-web-application-developer

Jiga: Full Stack Product Engineer

Headquarters: Anywhere
    URL: http://https:/jiga.io/about-us


What we're building
Jigais on a mission to help engineers build physical products faster. Thinknpm installfor mechanical engineers - we're building the infrastructure that makes hardware development as fast as software.
How we actually work
Were a small remote team made up of the best of the best. Our team members are distributed around the globe. While most of our product and engineering talent is located in Europe and Israel, youll also work with people from the US and Asia. Most of our work is made async, which is the secret sauce of our success.
High trust, low bullshit:We don't count hours or peek over your shoulder on Slack. We trust you to get your work done and tell us when something's wrong. You'll have real ownership over what you build: which means you'll make a lot of decisions about architecture and functionality without endless approval cycles. (If that sounds terrifying, we're probably not a good fit. If that sounds exciting, keep reading.)
Question everything:See something that doesn't make sense? Say it. Have a better way to do something? Just do it. We actually mean it when we say we want people to challenge the status quo and improve things. Our internal motto is Dont drink the kool-aid
No stupid Meetings:One weekly all-hands. One dev team sync. That's literally it. Everything else happens async in Slack or Loom. Your calendar will be beautifully, gloriously empty.
Actually friendly, not corporate friendly:We play games online every week (current favorite: Make it Meme). Once a year we fly everyone somewhere beautiful for our offsite (Greece, here we come). We genuinely like hanging out together, which turns out to be way better than forced "team building exercises."
What we value in engineering:
Simple > Complicated.Simple code, simple architecture; Simple solutions are better than complex ones.
Ship it, then improve it.Perfection is the enemy of done. Launch now, iterate forever.
Product > Engineering.Every line of code should make our users' lives better. We're not here to show off our algorithmic prowess - we're here to solve real business problems.
Financials
Jiga is fully funded, cashflow positive, with growing revenue MoM. We're completely transparent about our runway and finances - ask us anything.
You'll love it here if

You want to actually own things.Not "ownership" where you need three approvals to change a button color. Real ownership where you decide what to build, how to build it, and when to ship it.
You're genuinely full-stack- you're equally happy building a slick UI component or optimizing a database query. There's no task you'd refuse because it's "not your specialty."
You care about the product, not just the code. You want to understandwhywe're building something and you'll push back if it doesn't make sense.
You are motivated to run a marathonand ring the bell with us in 3-4 years from now.
Bureaucracy makes you want to scream. Multiple approval layers, process for the sake of process, corporate theatre - if these sound like your nightmare, welcome home.
You love shipping.Like, you get genuinely excited when you push to production. That "it's alive!" feeling never gets old.
You work fastbecause you're having fun, not because someone's watching you.

This might not be for you if

You hate ambiguity. You prefer clear, detailed task assignments and well-defined requirements
You like having management to check in, review and verify your work multiple times until its perfect
You're looking for a cuddly, 9-5, corporate job where you can coast a bit
You like the smell of gasoline and motor oil while driving to the office every day (sorry, we are 100% remote)
You like weeks of architecting over-complicated solutions

(No judgment if that's what you want - it's just not what we are.)
What you need

3+ years building full-stack web applications end-to-end
Strong at React + Node.js. MongoDB experience is a great plus.
Experience building complex applications - you understand clean architecture, security, scaling, performance, and maintainability
Solid data modeling fundamentals
Product company experience (you've felt the joy and pain of real users)
Some overlap with GMT+3 working hours so we can actually talk to you sometimes

What we offer
No ping pong tables. No beer kegs. No "unlimited vacation" that nobody takes. No ice cream fridge at the office. Oh right, we don't even have an office.
Here's what we do have:

A small team where you matter- we never compromise on people, that means you are part of the best team in the world.
Zero bureaucracy- we hate process theatre as much as you do
Real ownership and responsibility- make decisions, ship code, own the outcomes. Have real impact on the product from day 1.
Complete flexibility- work from anywhere, set your own hours, take time off when you need it (parents and DMs are very welcome)
Genuinely high trust- we trust you to do great work and be honest when things go sideways
A team that actually likes each other- international, diverse, genuinely friendly people who enjoy working together
Generous stock options- were looking for partners to run a marathon with us, you will get a life-changing shares when we get to the finish line
Competitive salary and PTOs- so you can also enjoy, relax and recharge
Self-development budgetfor books, courses, conferences, whatever helps you grow
Annual offsitein beautiful places (greece, here we come!)
Fast-paced environmentwith tons of creative freedom
Hard, interesting problems with ateam that's positioned to win big

fields.raw_text:
WodBoard: Senior Rails developer

Headquarters: London
    URL: https://www.wodboard.com


We're looking for a senior rails developer to come work with us at WodBoard WodBoard is gym management software that helps gym owners run their businesses and helps their customers, the gym members, live healthier lives. The brand name won't make any sense unless you've walked into a functional fitness gym before so I'll move swiftly on...We're a bootstrapped company so there's no VCs to answer to. That doesn't mean we're not ambitious though - there's a massive market we're going after and we want to create lasting change. As a combination of these two things we've a heavy focus on getting stuff done.Our development ethos could be best described as "full DHH". Whilst there's some bits we don't 100% agree with we stick to the core Rails ethos and stack, focussing on what we can achieve with the technology, rather than the technology itself. If you've enjoyed some of the blog posts on how Basecamp structure code, or enjoy the work of boringrails.com, you'd like working with us.We're a small (but mighty) tech team of 4 so you'll be jumping straight in and writing code for customers from day 1. There's also infrastructure/UI work/mobile app development work that happens and you can become involved in if you so wish. The role has the opportunity to build into a CTO role for the right person.A little more about the role and us:

It's really refreshing using technology to do something that helps people in a real world tangible way. Changing lives and increasing health through technology is very motivating!
We love simplicity. We're fanatical about it. This goes from our codebase, to our infrastructure, to how we operate as a company. It can be harder work upfront but it sure makes life easier down the road.
You'll need strong ownership skills. As a small team we don't have project managers. You're responsible for your tasks so you'll need to be good at taking ownership and reporting back to the team.
An ability to renegotiate requirements as you get into the technical details is most welcome! In Computer Science there's hard problems and hard problems that don't need solving. We are constantly asking ourselves if there's an easier way to do something.
We spend a lot of time talking to our customers and understanding their problems. This won't ever change. Be prepared to go back and evaluate previously held assumptions on new features after testing with beta customers

The position is fulltime and by no means do you need to be into health/fitness to work here (only about 50% of our staff are). It's fully remote position but you'd need to be on an EU timezone so there's sufficient overlap with the rest of the team. We also do a full team meetup in person twice per year.

To apply: https://weworkremotely.com/remote-jobs/wodboard-senior-rails-developer-1

fields.raw_text:
PostHog: Product Engineer - Data Modeling

Headquarters: San Francisco
    URL: https://posthog.com/


About PostHog
Weequip every developer to build successful products.
We started with open-source product analytics,launched out of Y Combinator's W20 cohort.
We've since shippedmore than a dozen products, includinga built-in data warehouse,a customer data platform, andMax AI, an AI-powered analyst that answers product questions, helps users find useful session recordings, and writes custom SQL queries.
Next on the roadmap are messaging, customer analytics, ai task creation and coding based on customer data, logs and support analytics.
Ourvaluesare not a poster on the wall full of aspiration. Theyve come from how we really work, day in day out.
PostHog isopen sourceproduct led, and adefault alivecompany that is well funded.
What you'll be doing
As a Product Engineer - Data Modeling s on the Data Stack team, youll build end user tools for understanding and traversing their data models.
Youll work on materializing user defined queries, and schedule & resolve DAGs of query materialization.
Youll debug stateful data workflows by digging into k8s pod metrics, and schedule jobs usingTemporal.io. As you can see, theres a huge breadth of challenges and opportunities to tackle, and nothing is off-limits.
The PostHog Data Stack is both a core product for our users and a foundational platform for our internal teams. Data is a first-class product at PostHog, not an afterthought.
You will have the chance to push the boundaries of what our Data Stack team can do while ensuring we remain stable and production-ready.
You now know what youll be doing, but what about what youll need to bring along?
Youll fit right in if:

Youre a builder.You bring strong skills in building resilient systems, with experience in Kubernetes, Docker, and S3 at scale. We build in python. Async-python andTemporal.ioskills are welcome.
You have good practices around building resilient systems.Logging, testing and monitoring (observability), but you are also comfortable with debugging stateful, async data workflows by digging into k8s pod metrics.
You are proficient in building UIs for data intensive tools.React is part of your toolset.
You bring experience with DAGs and Batch processing.Having used Dbt is a plus.
You bring a mix of skills.Its not just about the query engine. Youll need strong backend skills as we run a complex system.
You love getting things done.Engineers at PostHog have an incredible amount of autonomy to decide what to work on, so youll need to be proactive and justgitit done.
Youre ready to do the best work of your career.We have incredible distribution, a big financial cushion and an amazing team. Theres probably no better place to see how far you can go.

If this sounds like you, we should talk.
We are committed to ensuring a fair and accessible interview process. If you need any accommodations or adjustments, please let us know.

To apply: https://weworkremotely.com/remote-jobs/posthog-product-engineer-data-modeling

fields.raw_text:
PostHog: AI Product Engineer

Headquarters: San Francisco
    URL: https://posthog.com/


About PostHog
We're shipping every product that companies need to run their business from their first day, to the day they IPO, and beyond. The operating system for folks who build software.
We started with open-source product analytics,launched out of Y Combinator's W20 cohort. We've since shipped more than a dozen productsincluding:

A built-in data warehouse, so users can query product and customer data together using custom SQL insights.
A customer data platform, so they can send their data wherever they need with ease.
PostHog AI, an AI-powered analyst that answers product questions, helps users find useful session recordings, and writes custom SQL queries.

Next on the roadmap are CRM, messaging, revenue analytics, and support products. When we say every product that companies need to run their business, we really mean it!
We are:
1. Product-led. More than 100,000 companies have installed PostHog, mostly driven by word-of-mouth. We have intensely strong product-market fit.2. Default alive. Revenue is growing 10% MoM on average, and we're very efficient. We raise money to push ambition and grow faster, not to keep the lights on.3. Well-funded. We've raised more than $100m from some of the world's top investors. We're set up for a long, ambitious journey.
We're focused on building an awesome product for end users, hiring exceptional teammates, shipping fast, andbeing as weird as possible.
Things we care about

Transparency: Everyone can read about our roadmap, how we pay (or even let go of) people, our strategy, and how we work, in our public company handbook. Internally, we share revenue, notes and slides from board meetings, and fundraising plans, so everyone has the context they need to make good decisions.
Autonomy: We dont tell anyone what to do. Everyone chooses what to work on next based on what's going to have the biggest impact on our customers, and what they find interesting and motivating to work on. Engineers lead product teams and make product decisions. Teams are flexible and easy to change when needed.
Shipping fast: Why not now? We want to build a lot of products; we can't do that shipping at a normal pace. We've built the company around small teams  autonomous, highly-efficient groups of cracked engineers who can outship much larger companies because they own their products end-to-end.
Time for building: Nothing gets shipped in a meeting. We're a natively remote company. We default to async communication  PRs > Issues > Slack. Tuesdays and Thursdays aremeeting-free days, and we prioritize heads down building time over perfect coordination. This will be the most productive job you've ever had.
Ambition: We want to solve big problems. We strongly believe that aiming for the best possible upside, and sometimes missing, is better than never trying. We're optimistic about what's possible and our ability to get there.
Being weird: Weird means redesigning an already world-class website for the 5th time. It means shipping literally every product that relates to customer data. It means building an objectively unnecessary developer toy with dubious shareholder value. Doing weird stuff is a competitive advantage. And it's fun.

Who we're looking for
Were looking for a full-stack engineer who knows how to leverage LLMs to make PostHog 10x more powerful. Youve built and shipped agentic AI applications before and understand its more than just hitting an API with a good prompt.
Youll fit right in if you:

Ship end-to-end AI apps  from backend infra to frontend UX.
Collaborate widely  work across teams, find the right people, and make progress fast.
Think like a product builder  care about users and outcomes, not just code.

If youve worked in autonomous agents, workflow automation, or AI copilots before, youll feel at home  but here youll get to build it from scratch, in the open, with massive impact.
What makes this role unique
In this role, youre not hacking together an AI agent hoping someone will use it  youre building on top of a firehose of real customer data with immediate impact, whether that means creating new AI-powered tools or building observability features that help others understand how their agents perform in the wild.

Impact from day one: Youre building agents on top of real customer data  not toy demos, not when we get users.
Data advantage: PostHog already collects all the context agents need to be useful: analytics, sessions, events, feature flags, and more. Youll build on top of it all.
Agents that matter: Instead of copilots on the side, youll create background agents embedded into engineering workflows - changing how software gets built. Or, you might focus on building the analytics and observability layer around those agents - surfacing insights, clustering behaviors, and measuring model quality so teams can improve their own AI systems with confidence.
Build in the open: Work with feedback from the largest open-source product engineering communities in the world.

What you'll be doing

Owning products and features from beginning to end. This means originating ideas based on your intuition, talking to users, and understanding our strategy and goals. It means testing MVPs in production with real users. It meansiterating on their feedback, owning pricing, and ensuring the ongoing success of your work.
Collaborating with design (when necessary). Product engineers at PostHog are full-stack, so we expect you to ship and own the basic UX of your work usingour design system. From there, it's up to you to decide when to collaborate with our design team to iterate and polish the experience.
Implementing AI features. LLMs, eh? They're gettingprettaaay, prettaay good. All our products integrate with PostHog AI, so you'll likely be working with the PostHog AI team to implement AI features in your products. For some teams, that means designing observability and evaluation features for AI products.
Talking to users. Good product engineers read feedback from users and iterate quickly. Great product engineers have users they're friendly with, talk with them frequently, bounce ideas off them, and iterate with them when they ship new things.
Doing support. Every week, one person in each engineering team is designated the Support hero. Their job is to investigate and resolve issues reported by customers for their product. Giving users support from real engineers and shipping fixes and improvements in real-time is one of the best ways to spark joy in users. This role will also include some on-call time, too.
Writing docs. We have a content team that will collaborate with you on reviewing, polishing, and improving your documentation, but the best person to document a new feature is the person who built it.

Requirements

Full-stack experience with relevant technologies  e.g. Python or similar, React or similar, something to do with big data is a bonus.
Prior experience in AI workflow automation, copilots, or autonomous agent products.
Ability to choose pragmatic architectures, ship quickly, and iterate based on real feedback.
Strong sense for UX and product polish.
Excellent communicator who thrives on collaboration across teams.

Nice to have

Have worked at a high-growth SaaS company before.
Extensive knowledge of Django and/or TypeScript-based React.
Experience building AI-native products or integrating AI into existing software.

If you have a disability, please let us know if there's any way we can make the interview process better for you - we're happy to accommodate!

To apply: https://weworkremotely.com/remote-jobs/posthog-ai-product-engineer

To further develop and enhance our applications, we are looking for an experienced Full Stack Software Engineer on a Senior Level to join our multinational Scrum team. Required Skills and Qualifications

Extensive experience with React.js, JavaScript/TypeScript, HTML5, and CSS3.
Strong background in cloud infrastructure with hands-on experience building and operating cloud-native applications using Azure, AWS or GCP

Customer-first mindset with a focus on usability and performance.

fields.raw_text:
Summer Research Early Identification Program (SR-EIP) Fully Funded Internship for Undergraduates: Apply Now!

Are you an undergraduate student with a strong interest in research and long-term plans to pursue a PhD or MD-PhD? The SR-EIP (Summer Research Early Identification Program), organized by The Leadership Alliance, is now open for applications for the 2026 cohort, with a deadline of February 3, 2026. This prestigious and fully funded summer research opportunity is designed to identify, train, and mentor promising undergraduatesparticularly those who may not yet have had access to intensive research experiencesand prepare them for competitive doctoral programs.

About the Summer Research Early Identification Program (SR-EIP)
SR-EIP is a fully paid summer internship program that offers undergraduate students hands-on, closely mentored research experiences across a wide range of disciplines. The program focuses on building a strong foundation in research methodology, critical thinking, and academic inquiry while exposing participants to the realities and expectations of graduate-level research.
Participants spend 8 to 10 weeks during the summer at one of 20+ leading research institutions in the United States. During this period, students work directly with faculty members or senior researchers who provide individualized mentorship and guidance. Research areas span:

Life and physical sciences
Social and behavioral sciences
Humanities

The goal of SR-EIP is not only to introduce students to research but to prepare them strategically for future PhD or MD-PhD applications, positioning them for long-term success in academia and research-driven careers.

What the Program Offers
The SR-EIP stands out as one of the most comprehensive undergraduate research programs available. Selected participants benefit from:

A fully funded experience, including a stipend, housing, and travel support provided by the host institution
Hands-on research training, combining theoretical knowledge with practical laboratory, field, or archival work
One-on-one mentorship from faculty or research professionals in the students chosen field
Professional development support, including guidance on graduate school applications and academic career pathways
Opportunities to present research, through oral or poster presentations at the Leadership Alliance National Symposium
Long-term access to mentoring and professional networks as part of The Leadership Alliance alumni community

Notably, 45% of SR-EIP participants have never taken part in a summer research program before, making this initiative especially valuable for students who are early in their research journey.

Who Is Eligible to Apply?
To be eligible for the 2026 Summer Research Early Identification Program, applicants must meet the following criteria:

Be a U.S. citizen, U.S. non-citizen national, or permanent resident with valid documentation at the time of application
International students on F-1 visas, as well as asylum seekers and refugees, are not eligible
Be enrolled full-time in an accredited public or private college or university in the United States or its territories
Be in good academic standing, with a minimum GPA of 3.0
Have completed at least two semesters of undergraduate study and have at least one semester remaining before graduation by the start of the program
Demonstrate a clear and committed interest in pursuing graduate study toward a PhD or MD-PhD

Important note: SR-EIP is not intended for students pursuing professional degrees in law, business administration, clinical medicine, or allied health professions.

How to Apply
Applications for the 2026 SR-EIP cycle open on November 1, 2025 and must be submitted online through The Leadership Alliance application portal.
Applicants are advised to carefully review the Application Instructions and Frequently Asked Questions(FAQs) before applying.
A complete application includes:

The online application form
Two letters of recommendation
Official academic transcript(s)

It is the applicants responsibility to ensure that all materials are received by the February 3, 2026 deadline. Late or incomplete applications will not be considered.

Research Sites and Institutions
With one application, students may apply to up to three different research sites. Participating institutions include some of the most respected universities and research organizations in the U.S., such as:

Harvard University
Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)
Stanford University
Yale University
Princeton University
Columbia University
Johns Hopkins University
University of Pennsylvania
Vanderbilt University
Brown University
Caltech
Cornell University
Howard University
Emory University
Weill Cornell Medical College
Regeneron
AbbVie
And many more

Each institution offers unique research areas and program structures, so applicants are encouraged to review individual site requirements carefully.

Commitment to Diversity and Inclusion
The Leadership Alliance is deeply committed to diversity, equity, and inclusion. Its programs are designed to prepare scholars from underrepresented and underserved backgrounds for advanced graduate training. Applications are reviewed without discrimination based on race, color, sex, age, religion, national or ethnic origin, disability, veteran status, socioeconomic background, sexual orientation, gender identity, or gender expression.

Why SR-EIP Matters
SR-EIP alumni include doctoral scholars and researchers who credit the program with clarifying their academic goals, strengthening their research skills, and opening doors to elite graduate programs. Through mentorship, exposure, and sustained support, SR-EIP continues to play a critical role in shaping the next generation of scholars across STEM, social sciences, and the humanities.
If you are serious about a future in research and graduate study, the Summer Research Early Identification Program is an opportunity you should not miss.

Subscribe to OFYfor more opportunities like this
The post Summer Research Early Identification Program (SR-EIP) Fully Funded Internship for Undergraduates: Apply Now! appeared first on Opportunities for Youth.

Enterprising Futures Scholarship 2026: Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs Supports Young Impact Entrepreneurs

The Enterprising Futures Scholarship 2026, powered by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs in partnership with One Young World, is now open for applications. This prestigious scholarship is designed for young entrepreneurs and business leaders who are leading or contributing to scalable start-ups and SMEs with social or environmental impact, particularly across Africa and the Middle East.
As young people increasingly shape the future of global economies, entrepreneurship has become a powerful force for sustainable development. Yet, many promising entrepreneurs face barriers such as limited access to international networks, resources, and global exposure. The Enterprising Futures Scholarship addresses these gaps by connecting high-impact entrepreneurs to a global leadership platform.
About the Scholarship
The scholarship enables selected entrepreneurs to attend the One Young World Summit 2026 in Cape Town, where over 2,000 young leaders from more than 190 countries will convene to exchange ideas, learn from world-class experts, and collaborate on solutions to pressing global challenges.
Beyond the Summit, scholars become part of a broader ecosystem supported by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs, offering long-term opportunities for engagement, visibility, and collaboration.
What Scholars Receive
Selected scholars will benefit from:


Full participation in the One Young World Summit 2026


Access to a global network of young leaders, entrepreneurs, and policymakers


Opportunities to strengthen entrepreneurial and leadership skills


International exposure for their ventures and impact work


Engagement in pre- and post-programme activities led by the Dutch MFA and partners


Previous scholars have contributed to ecosystem mapping, advised on development initiatives, and participated in events organised by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs and its partners.
Who Can Apply
Applicants must:


Be 1835 years old by November 2026


Be leading or part of a scalable start-up or SME with demonstrable social and/or environmental impact


Be a national and resident of one of the eligible countries, including: Ethiopia, Jordan, Lebanon, Mozambique, Uganda, Tunisia, Palestine, Egypt, Cte dIvoire, Kenya, Morocco, Nigeria, Senegal, Benin, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ghana, South Africa, Burundi, Iraq (including Kurdistan region of Iraq), Sudan, Mali, and Algeria.

Have a working proficiency in English

Be available to participate fully in the programme between 30 October  7 November 2026, including pre- and post-programme activities


The Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs strongly encourages applications from entrepreneurs of all backgrounds and identities, including those from underserved and rural communities.
Key Dates


Applications Open: 19 January 2026


Application Deadline: 9 March 2026


How to Apply
Eligible candidates must apply through the official application portal.
Apply Here
For more opportunities,click here.
The post Enterprising Futures Scholarship 2026: Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs Supports Young Impact Entrepreneurs appeared first on Opportunities for Youth.

AsiaGlobal Fellows Program 2026  A Premier Leadership Fellowship for Global Changemakers

The AsiaGlobal Fellows Program, hosted by the Asia Global Institute (AGI) at The University of Hong Kong, is now accepting applications for its 2026 cohort. Launched in 2017, the program is dedicated to cultivating a new generation of global leaders who are equipped to understand and address complex challenges from an Asian perspective.
To date, the fellowship has supported 104 Fellows from over 55 countries, bringing together diverse mid-career professionals committed to public policy, global governance, economic development, sustainability, and social impact.
About the Program
The AsiaGlobal Fellows Program is an interdisciplinary, fully immersive leadership development experience based in Hong Kong. Through:

A rigorous curriculum
Experiential learning
Dialogue with world-class experts
Engagement with scholars, policymakers, and business leaders

Fellows gain deep insights into geopolitics, economics, sustainability, technology, and governance, with a strong focus on understanding global issues through Asian lenses.
The fellowship is directed by Asia Global Institute (AGI), a multidisciplinary institute that provides a platform to explore timely global challenges and fosters informed, solutions-oriented dialogue.

Application Deadline
March 31, 2026

Who Should Apply?
The program welcomes candidates from any country, background, or sector. To be eligible, applicants must:

Be mid-career professionals with 825 years of experience
Be active in public policy, politics, civil society, academia, or business
Demonstrate a strong interest in the Asia-Pacific region
Show a proven capacity to create positive impact in their organization and society

AGI values diversity and particularly encourages applicants with varied professional experiences and cultural perspectives.

Language Requirement
All program activities and materials are in English. High proficiency in reading, writing, speaking, and listening is required.

Application Components
Online Application Only
All submissions must be completed through the online portal. No emailed applications will be processed.
Three Recommendation Letters
Referees (non-relatives who know your work) must submit letters directly in English.
Applications with missing letters will be marked incomplete.
Supporting Documents
Applicants may submit resumes, awards, citations, publications, or other materials to strengthen their application.
Interview (If Shortlisted)
Shortlisted candidates will be invited to an online or in-person interview during the evaluation period.

Why Join the AsiaGlobal Fellows Program?
Fellows benefit from:

Direct engagement with global thinkers, academics, and policymakers
A strong, diverse global alumni network
Deep exposure to emerging issues shaping Asia and the world
Opportunities to expand leadership capacity and policy influence

The program is ideal for professionals seeking to broaden their global mindset and contribute meaningfully to public policy and global governance.
Applications for the 2026 cohort are open until March 31. Apply now.

The post AsiaGlobal Fellows Program 2026  A Premier Leadership Fellowship for Global Changemakers appeared first on Opportunities for Youth.

fields.raw_text:
EU Women Leaders 2026: Accelerating Women into Executive and Board Roles

A Free EU Co-Funded Programme for Senior Women Professionals
Women across Europe remain underrepresented in executive management and board-level positions, despite their qualifications, leadership experience, and proven capabilities. With the new EU Directive on gender balance on boards set to come into force in June 2026, the conversation has shifted. The question is no longer whether women should be at the decision-making table, but whether they are fully supported, visible, and prepared to access these roles. To address this challenge, EU Women Leaders 2026 has been launched as a free, selective, and EU co-financed leadership programme. The initiative is designed to accelerate senior women into executive and board-level positions across corporate, academic, and non-profit sectors.

Programme Overview
EU Women Leaders 2026 is a hybrid leadership development programme running from February to June 2026. It combines online expert-led sessions with hands-on workshops and culminates in an in-person networking event in Luxembourg.
Key features include:

Free EU co-financed training delivered over several months.
Weekly online sessions led by experts in leadership, governance, and executive communication.
Hands-on workshops focused on strategic positioning and board readiness.
Advanced training modules covering governance, leadership, and executive communication.
Certificate of completion awarded to all participants.
In-person networking event in Luxembourg, included as part of the programme.

This structure ensures that participants not only gain knowledge but also practical skills and visibility, positioning them for the next level of leadership.

Eligibility and Selection
The programme is open to senior women professionals in the European Union who are ready to step into executive management and board positions. Applicants may come from corporate, academic, or non-profit sectors.
Selection process:

Applications are open now and will close on January 27, 2026, just before midnight.
A two-phase process will be used: written application followed by a short interview.
Only 20 women will be selected to join the programme.
Results will be shared prior to the programmes start in the second week of February 2026.

This selective approach ensures that participants are highly motivated and positioned to benefit fully from the training and networking opportunities.

Why This Programme Matters
The EU Women Leaders 2026 initiative is a strategic intervention aimed at reshaping leadership in Europe. By preparing women for executive and board-level roles, the programme directly supports the implementation of the EU Directive on gender balance.
The initiative acknowledges that capability alone is not enough. Visibility, readiness, and systemic support are equally critical. As Carol Constant, one of the programmes leaders and 2025 Most Influential HR CEO in Central Europe, emphasized, This is not just a training programme; its an opportunity to position yourself for the next level of leadership and shape the future of decision-making in Europe.

Organizers and Partners
EU Women Leaders 2026 is spearheaded by Lucia de Luca at DeLucaStrategy and WhomLab, an HR technology company focused on quality hiring and team management. The programme is co-funded by the European Union, ensuring accessibility and credibility.
The initiative builds on existing EU projects such as the Erasmus+ Board Readiness Project, reinforcing the broader European commitment to gender balance in leadership.

Application Details

Deadline: January 27, 2026 (just before midnight).
Programme dates: February  June 2026.
Format: Hybrid (online weekly sessions + in-person event in Luxembourg).
Cost: Free, co-financed by the EU.
Selection: 20 participants through application and interview.
Outcome: Certificate of completion and enhanced readiness for executive and board roles.

Interested candidates are encouraged to apply promptly and to tag other women leaders who could benefit from this opportunity.

EU Women Leaders 2026 represents a timely and impactful initiative to accelerate women into executive and board-level positions across Europe. With the EU Directive on gender balance set to take effect in June 2026, this programme provides senior women professionals with the tools, training, and visibility they need to step confidently into leadership roles. Apply now.

The post EU Women Leaders 2026: Accelerating Women into Executive and Board Roles appeared first on Opportunities for Youth.

With Youth For Youth (WYFY) Grant Opportunities for Western New York: Youth-Led Funding to Transform Out-of-School-Time Programs Across WNY

With Youth For Youth (WYFY) is launching a major grant opportunity for Western New York organizations committed to elevating youth voice and transforming out-of-school-time (OST) programs. Coordinated by Youthprise and funded by the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation and the Ralph C. Wilson, Jr. Foundation, WYFY is a national initiative empowering young people to redesign afterschool and youth development systems from the ground up.
This initiative partners sites across Missouri, Minnesota, Southeast Michigan, Vermont, and Western New York, building on earlier youth-centered projectsGenerator Z and Powered by Youth Voiceto reimagine afterschool learning through collaborative design, creativity, and paid youth participation.

About the Grant
Beginning in 2026, the WNY WYFY Youth Advisory Boarda group of 24 youth ages 1317will distribute over $2 million in grants to programs that uplift youth voice, ensure equitable access, and contribute to systems-level improvements in the OST ecosystem.
Funding is available for organizations that:

Meaningfully integrate youth leadership and decision-making
Provide strong, relevant, and beneficial experiences for young people
Serve communities across the nine WNY counties
Demonstrate clear goals, responsible use of funds, and impact
Present strong solutions to challenges facing youth
Contribute to broader systems change in OST

Grant Amounts:

Minimum: $25,000
Maximum: $150,000

Funding may support existing programs or new initiatives, as long as they center youth voice and leadership.

Eligibility
Applicants must be:

501(c)(3) nonprofit organizations, government agencies, OR schools
Located in or serving Western New Yorks nine counties:
Allegany, Chautauqua, Cattaraugus, Erie, Genesee, Monroe, Niagara, Orleans, Wyoming
Providing programs for youth ages 518 outside school hours

Ineligible requests include tackle football, school-sanctioned sports teams, equipment-only funding, multi-year requests, endowments, and religious programming.

Why Youth Voice Matters  In Youths Own Words
WYFY aims to build a regional system where young people are co-creators, decision-makers, and system leadersnot just program participants.

Out-of-School-Time (OST)  A Broad, Inclusive Definition
OST includes a range of youth supports, such as:

Afterschool & drop-in programs
Non-school community sports
Arts, culture, and enrichment
Leadership development & civic engagement
Youth workforce & career readiness
Library programs
Prevention & restorative initiatives

WYFYs holistic approach views OST as an ecosystem, not a set of separate services.

How to Apply
Applications must be submitted online through the Foundant Grant Lifecycle Manager.
No emailed, paper, or PDF submissions are accepted.
Key Dates:

Application opens: January 20, 2026
Virtual Info Session: January 21, 2026 at 3:30 p.m.
(Zoom link provided in original announcement)
Deadline: February 23, 2026, at 4:00 p.m.
Decisions announced: April 2026
Funds distributed: June 2026 (for one-year programming)

Applications will be evaluated on:

Youth Voice & Leadership

With Youth For Youth (WYFY) Grant Opportunities for Western New York: Youth-Led Funding to Transform Out-of-School-Time Programs Across WNY

With Youth For Youth (WYFY) is launching a major grant opportunity for Western New York organizations committed to elevating youth voice and transforming out-of-school-time (OST) programs. Coordinated by Youthprise and funded by the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation and the Ralph C. Wilson, Jr. Foundation, WYFY is a national initiative empowering young people to redesign afterschool and youth development systems from the ground up.
This initiative partners sites across Missouri, Minnesota, Southeast Michigan, Vermont, and Western New York, building on earlier youth-centered projectsGenerator Z and Powered by Youth Voiceto reimagine afterschool learning through collaborative design, creativity, and paid youth participation.

About the Grant
Beginning in 2026, the WNY WYFY Youth Advisory Boarda group of 24 youth ages 1317will distribute over $2 million in grants to programs that uplift youth voice, ensure equitable access, and contribute to systems-level improvements in the OST ecosystem.
Funding is available for organizations that:

Meaningfully integrate youth leadership and decision-making
Provide strong, relevant, and beneficial experiences for young people
Serve communities across the nine WNY counties
Demonstrate clear goals, responsible use of funds, and impact
Present strong solutions to challenges facing youth
Contribute to broader systems change in OST

Grant Amounts:

Minimum: $25,000
Maximum: $150,000

Funding may support existing programs or new initiatives, as long as they center youth voice and leadership.

Eligibility
Applicants must be:

501(c)(3) nonprofit organizations, government agencies, OR schools
Located in or serving Western New Yorks nine counties:
Allegany, Chautauqua, Cattaraugus, Erie, Genesee, Monroe, Niagara, Orleans, Wyoming
Providing programs for youth ages 518 outside school hours

Ineligible requests include tackle football, school-sanctioned sports teams, equipment-only funding, multi-year requests, endowments, and religious programming.

Why Youth Voice Matters  In Youths Own Words
WYFY aims to build a regional system where young people are co-creators, decision-makers, and system leadersnot just program participants.

Out-of-School-Time (OST)  A Broad, Inclusive Definition
OST includes a range of youth supports, such as:

Afterschool & drop-in programs
Non-school community sports
Arts, culture, and enrichment
Leadership development & civic engagement
Youth workforce & career readiness
Library programs
Prevention & restorative initiatives

WYFYs holistic approach views OST as an ecosystem, not a set of separate services.

How to Apply
Applications must be submitted online through the Foundant Grant Lifecycle Manager.
No emailed, paper, or PDF submissions are accepted.
Key Dates:

Application opens: January 20, 2026
Virtual Info Session: January 21, 2026 at 3:30 p.m.
(Zoom link provided in original announcement)
Deadline: February 23, 2026, at 4:00 p.m.
Decisions announced: April 2026
Funds distributed: June 2026 (for one-year programming)

Applications will be evaluated on:

Youth Voice & Leadership
Youth Experience & Benefits
Mission, Values & Impact
Goals, Outcomes & Use of Funds
Challenges & Solutions
Systems-Level Thinking
Geographic Representation (consideration)

Youth reviewers (grades 812) will read and score applications.

Additional Expectations
Awarded organizations must provide a year-end report including:

Program outcomes
Budget expenditures
Lessons learned
Feedback on the youth-led grantmaking process

WYFY strongly encourages organizations to demonstrate how they will expand youth leadership, distribute decision-making power, and co-create programming with youth.

Together We Build a Youth-Led Future
WYFY strives to reshape how Western New York invests in its young peopleensuring fairness, equity, and youth-centered systems change. By putting decision-making into the hands of youth, this initiative supports programs that reflect the real needs, experiences, and aspirations of young people.

Apply here

fields.raw_text:
Opportunity: Altavoz Lab Community Journalist Fellowship 2026

Altavoz Lab has opened applications for the 2026 Community Journalist Fellowship, a seven-month program designed to empower local journalists serving communities historically marginalized or overlooked by mainstream media. The fellowship supports reporters rooted in their communities, working to uplift local voices and strengthen accountability through impactful storytelling.
About the Fellowship
Launching in April 2026, the program brings together a cohort of community-based journalists  freelancers or newsroom staff  reporting in English or Spanish. Fellows will receive up to $8,000 to produce an in-depth reporting project or series. Participating newsrooms will also receive up to $3,000 to deepen audience engagement beyond social media.
The fellowship is built for storytellers who live and work in communities with low civic participation, including borderland regions of AZ, NM, CA, TX, and states such as AR, FL, GA, KY, LA, MS, NC, SC, TN, PA, VA, WV, KS, OK, IL, as well as Puerto Rico.
Altavoz Lab centers journalists committed to community-driven narratives, cultural sensitivity, and collaborative journalism. Reporters from underrepresented racial, social, ethnic, and economic backgrounds are strongly encouraged to apply.

Key Benefits

Up to $8,000 reporting stipend
Up to $3,000 newsroom engagement support
Mentorship from experienced journalists
Audience engagement coaching
Monthly workshops, training, and a co-learning environment
Optional editorial support (editing, translation, fact-checking)
National community of fellows and peer support
Publication of the final story on AltavozLab.com


Eligibility Requirements
Applicants must:

Be freelancers or staff journalists reporting for community-based outlets
Live in the community they intend to cover
Serve underrepresented or historically disinvested communities
Work in English, Spanish, or both
Submit:

A budget for reporting + engagement
Resume and headshot
Contact of one professional reference
Signed editor consent form
30-minute interview if shortlisted



Altavoz alumni may reapply but not in consecutive years.

Important Dates

Applications Open: January 16, 2026
Webinar: Feb. 6, 2026  4:30 PM ET / 1:30 PM PT (English/Spanish)
Deadline: Feb. 16, 2026, 11:59 PM PT
Finalist Interviews: Week of March 10, 2026
Program Start: April 67, 2026 (Spanish/English cohorts)
Story Deadline: Oct. 30, 2026


Fellowship Expectations

Credit Altavoz Lab in all fellowship-related work
Attend all monthly cohort meetings & training sessions
Meet regularly with mentor and engagement coach
Submit progress updates, engagement data & impact surveys
Allow Altavoz Lab to publish your story and related materials

Newsrooms are encouraged to engage actively and may receive additional editorial support.

What Altavoz Lab Provides

Story-aligned mentorship
Audience engagement strategy and coaching
Editorial support (as needed)
Cross-country journalist community
A creative, collaborative learning space
Publication on AltavozLab.com


How to Apply
Submit your full application, including required documents and budget, through the link below.
Apply Here
Register for the Webinar


The post Opportunity: Altavoz Lab Community Journalist Fellowship 2026 appeared first on Opportunities for Youth.

fields.raw_text:
The LOral Fund for Women: Renewed Commitment to Global empowerment

Women across the globe continue to face disproportionate challenges in the wake of social, economic, and political crises. Recognizing this urgent reality, LOral launched the LOral Fund for Women in 2020 as part of its broader commitment to social responsibility. Since its inception, the Fund has become a vital source of support for frontline organizations working to protect and empower women and girls. After three years of impactful work, the Fund has been renewed for another three years (20232026) with a dedicated budget of 30 million, reaffirming LOrals ambition to address pressing global challenges and contribute to a fairer, more inclusive future.

Achievements Since 2020
In just its first three years of operation, the Fund supported over 530 frontline non-profit organizations worldwide. These organizations have directly impacted the lives of more than 4.8 million women and girls, providing essential services, resources, and opportunities. The scale of this outreach demonstrates the Funds ability to mobilize resources effectively and deliver tangible results in diverse contexts.
The organizations supported range from grassroots initiatives to international NGOs, each working to address critical issues such as poverty alleviation, access to education, healthcare, psychological support, and protection against violence. By channeling funds into these efforts, LOral has positioned itself as a key partner in advancing gender equality and womens rights.

Why Supporting Women Matters
The urgency of this mission is underscored by sobering global statistics:

Extreme poverty: In 2024, projections indicate that 24.3 million more women than men will be living in extreme poverty. At the current pace, eradicating extreme poverty among women could take another 137 years (UN Women, 2024).
Violence against women: Nearly one in three women worldwideapproximately 736 million individualshas experienced physical and/or sexual violence at least once in her lifetime. This figure excludes sexual harassment, meaning the true scale of violence is even greater (UN Women, 2024).
Aid gaps: Despite these realities, only 4% of bilateral international aid programs are primarily aimed at supporting women (OECD, 2022).

These figures highlight the systemic inequalities women face and the urgent need for targeted interventions. Supporting women is not only a matter of justice but also a prerequisite for building sustainable, inclusive societies.

Women in Armed Conflicts
Armed conflicts exacerbate the vulnerabilities of women and girls. The war in Ukraine, ongoing since 2022, has displaced more than 6.1 million people, marking the largest population displacement crisis since World War II (UNHCR, 2024). Of those displaced, 63% are women and children, underscoring the gendered impact of conflict.
Women in conflict zones are often exposed to torture, sexual abuse, and trafficking. Globally, 257 million women live in countries where conflicts intensify sexual violence (Care, 2024). Addressing these risks requires immediate and sustained support.
The LOral Fund for Women has partnered with organizations such as the Red Cross, SINGA, and UN agencies including the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and UNICEF. These collaborations focus on providing emergency assistanceshelter, healthcare, psychological and legal support, education, employment opportunities, and protection against trafficking and sexual violence. By supporting these initiatives, the Fund helps women and children rebuild their lives in the aftermath of conflict.

Renewed Commitment: 20232026
With its renewal for three additional years, the Fund has allocated 30 million to continue its mission. This investment reflects LOrals recognition that systemic change requires sustained effort. The renewed Fund will continue to prioritize:

Emergency response: Supporting women in crisis situations, particularly in conflict zones and areas affected by displacement.
Long-term empowerment: Funding initiatives that provide education, employment, and healthcare opportunities.
Advocacy and awareness: Highlighting the global inequalities women face and mobilizing resources to address them.

By extending its commitment, LOral ensures that millions more women and girls will benefit from targeted support, helping to close the gap in aid and opportunity.

The LOral Fund for Women stands as a powerful example of corporate responsibility in action. Since 2020, it has delivered measurable impact by supporting hundreds of organizations and millions of women worldwide. Its renewal through 2026, backed by 30 million, signals a continued dedication to addressing poverty, violence, and inequality. Apply here.

Aspen Institute Internships 2026 | Aspen Institute Internship Program for International Students and U.S. Students

Aspen Institute Internships offer students and recent graduates the opportunity to gain hands-on, real-world experience at one of the worlds most respected nonpartisan institutions. The Aspen Institute Internship Program is designed to immerse interns in meaningful work while providing professional development, mentorship, and exposure to influential leaders across policy, economics, education, security, culture, and social impact sectors.
From the first day, Aspen Institute interns are actively engaged in the Institutes daily operations and programmatic work. These internships are available across multiple offices in Aspen, Colorado; Washington, D.C.; New York City; and Chicago, offering a dynamic environment for individuals seeking careers in public policy, research, communications, leadership development, and nonprofit management.

Background: About the Aspen Institute Internship Program
The Aspen Institute is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to fostering leadership, encouraging dialogue, and advancing solutions to critical societal challenges. Through its internship program, the Institute provides a structured learning environment where interns work alongside experienced professionals and contribute directly to high-impact initiatives.
Interns participate not only in day-to-day program activities but also benefit from professional development workshops, internal events, and exposure to the Institutes renowned public forums such as the Aspen Ideas Festival, Aspen Security Forum, and Aspen Ideas: Climate. Many former interns have gone on to secure full-time roles within the Aspen Institute or pursue advanced studies at leading universities.

Eligibility Criteria: Who Can Apply for Aspen Institute Internships?
The Aspen Institute Internships are open to individuals who meet the following general eligibility requirements:

Current undergraduate or graduate students, or recent college graduates
Ability to work effectively in diverse teams
Strong communication, organizational, and research skills
Willingness to learn, adapt, and contribute in a fast-paced professional environment
Availability to work in-person or remotely depending on the role
Ability to commit to internship timelines, including summer 2026 programs

Some roles have additional requirements, such as:

Availability to travel to Aspen, Colorado
Proficiency in tools like Microsoft Office, Canva, WordPress, Salesforce, or CRM platforms
Academic background or strong interest in fields such as public policy, economics, international relations, communications, education, or business
Language skills (e.g., Spanish preferred for some roles but not mandatory)

Internships are open to applicants eligible to work in the United States. Specific visa sponsorship information is not stated and should be confirmed directly with the Aspen Institute.

Program Details: Structure, Locations, and Duration
The Aspen Institute Internship Program 2026 offers a wide range of internship placements across departments and programs. Internships are primarily summer-based, with varying structures:
Key Locations

Aspen, Colorado
Washington, D.C.
New York City
Chicago, Illinois

Internship Duration

Most internships run during Summer 2026
Some positions are full-time, others part-time
Certain roles require availability for specific event dates (e.g., July 2026 conferences)

Fields and Programs Available
Internship opportunities span numerous Aspen Institute programs, including but not limited to:

Ascend at the Aspen Institute
Aspen Conexin
Aspen Economic Strategy Group
Aspen Ideas Festival & Fellows Program
Aspen Leadership Seminars
Aspen Society
Aspen Strategy Group & Aspen Security Forum
Business & Society Program
Education & Society Program
Financial Security Program
Public Programs (Aspen Ideas: Climate)
Aspen Conference Services Team
Workplace Innovation Now (WIN) Challenge

Interns gain experience in research, policy analysis, communications, event planning, administration, data management, leadership development, and stakeholder engagement.

How to Apply: Aspen Institute Internship Application Process
Applicants interested in the Aspen Institute Internships 2026 should follow these steps:

Review the full list of available internship opportunities on the Aspen Institute careers page
Identify internship roles that align with your academic background and career interests
Prepare required application materials (as specified for each role)
Submit your application through the official Aspen Institute application portal
Direct any internship-related questions to internships@aspeninstitute.org

Each internship listing may have specific qualifications and expectations, so applicants are encouraged to carefully review individual descriptions before applying.

Important Dates and Deadlines

2026 Internship Application Window:
January 9  January 30, 2026

Applicants are strongly encouraged to apply early, as some roles may receive a high volume of applications.

Why Choose the Aspen Institute Internship Program?
The Aspen Institute Internship Program provides an unparalleled opportunity to:

Gain hands-on experience in high-impact policy and leadership initiatives
Work alongside globally respected experts and practitioners
Build professional networks across sectors and disciplines
Develop practical skills in research, communication, event management, and strategy
Contribute meaningfully to programs shaping global and national dialogue

Former interns consistently describe the program as career-defining, with many transitioning into long-term roles within the Institute or advancing to graduate studies.

Apply Here: Aspen Institute Internships 2026


The Aspen Institute Internships 2026 represent an exceptional opportunity for students and recent graduates seeking meaningful professional experience in leadership, policy, and social impact. With placements across multiple locations and disciplines, the Aspen Institute Internship Program equips participants with real-world skills, mentorship, and exposure to influential global conversations.
If you are motivated, curious, and eager to grow professionally while contributing to impactful work, the Aspen Institute Internships are a powerful step toward your future.

For more opportunities visit Opportunities for youth

Pre-Doctoral Research Fellow Opportunity at University of Oxford (Remote, Part-Time)

The Pre-Doctoral Research Fellow opportunity for candidates interested in advancing their expertise in Human-AI Interaction (HAI), Empirical Operations Management, and Machine Learning applications in business, is open by the University of Oxford, through its Sad Business School. This position is designed for individuals aiming to pursue a PhD in the next one to two years, serving as a specialized pathway into Professor Kejia Hus doctoral research group.
Advance Your AI and Business Research Career
The Pre-Doctoral Research Fellow role provides a unique opportunity to work remotely with leading Oxford scholars on high-impact research. Fellows will contribute to projects at the intersection of AI, machine learning, and business decision-making, gaining experience with cutting-edge technologies such as large language models (LLMs) like GPT. This position also offers an avenue to strengthen your academic profile, including strong reference letters for PhD and Masters applications, while participating in a flexible, remote work environment.
Eligibility Criteria
Candidates for this Pre-Doctoral Research Fellow position should meet the following requirements:

Educational Background: Strong foundation in Mathematics, Statistics, Computer Science, or Economics.
Technical Skills: Proficiency in Python or R for statistical programming, and knowledge of econometrics.
AI/ML Experience: Hands-on experience with large language models (GPT) and machine learning techniquesis highly desirable.
PhD Aspirations: Preference will be given to candidates planning to apply for a PhD within the next 1-2 years.
Commitment: Availability to work part-time until June 30, 2026.
Communication Skills: Strong oral and written communication abilities are essential.

This role is open globally for qualified candidates due to its remote work flexibility.

Program Details
The Pre-Doctoral Research Fellow position involves:

Start Date: Immediate, as soon as a suitable candidate is found.
Duration: Part-time until June 30, 2026, with potential for extension based on performance.
Structure: Remote, flexible working hours; collaboration with a multidisciplinary research team.
Key Responsibilities:

Conduct empirical research and develop advanced forecasting algorithms using statistical and machine learning methods.
Draft and contribute to academic publications and technical reports for both scholarly journals and industry partners.
Lead and participate in AI-focused research projects, with particular emphasis on LLMs for business applications.
Collaborate with researchers, practitioners, and students to achieve project objectives.



How to Apply
Interested candidates should submit the following documents to lixiang4016@gmail.com:

Curriculum Vitae (CV)
Academic Transcript

Applications are reviewed on a rolling basis, so early submission is strongly encouraged. Ensure that your materials highlight your quantitative expertise, experience with AI/ML, and PhD aspirations.
Important Deadlines

Rolling Applications: Apply as soon as possible to maximize your chance of consideration.
End Date of Program: June 30, 2026

Why Join the University of Oxford Research Team?
Joining Professor Kejia Hus team at Sad Business School offers unparalleled opportunities to:

Conduct cutting-edge AI and business research with Oxford faculty.
Strengthen your PhD or graduate school applications with strong reference letters.
Participate in innovative projects using advanced machine learning techniques and LLMs.
Collaborate in a flexible remote work environment with global researchers.

This fellowship serves as a gateway to a career in AI research, operations management, and business analytics, preparing candidates for both academic and industry roles.

Pre-Doctoral Research Fellow at University of Oxford
Email Application

For more opportunities visit Opportunities for youth

PhD Scholarships in Finance at Durham University Business School  Fully Funded Doctoral Opportunities for UK, EU, and International Students

PhD scholarships in Finance at Durham University Business School are now open for applications, offering fully funded doctoral opportunities for UK, EU, and international students who wish to pursue advanced research in finance. These PhD scholarships provide rigorous academic training, strong supervision, and generous financial support for qualified candidates seeking to become leading experts in the field of finance. With a strong research culture and excellent placement outcomes, Durham University Business School continues to attract talented doctoral researchers from around the world.
Introduction and Background to the PhD Scholarships in Finance
The PhD scholarships in Finance at Durham University Business School are designed to support outstanding students who wish to undertake full-time doctoral research in finance. Hosted by the Department of Finance at Durham University, the PhD (Finance) programme provides high-level research training aimed at preparing graduates for successful careers in academia, research institutions, and industry.
Faculty members in the Department of Finance conduct research across a wide range of finance fields and publish regularly in top-tier academic journals such as the Journal of Finance, Journal of Financial Economics, and the Review of Financial Studies. PhD students benefit from close academic supervision, a vibrant and collaborative research environment, and access to strong professional networks. These PhD scholarships in Finance form part of Durham University Business Schools broader commitment to research excellence and doctoral training.
Eligibility Criteria for the PhD Scholarships in Finance
The PhD scholarships in Finance at Durham University Business School are open to a wide range of applicants, depending on the specific funding scheme. Below are the eligibility details based strictly on the available information.
General Eligibility


Applicants must be seeking admission to the PhD (Finance) programme.


Study mode must be full-time.


Funding is available for UK students, EU students, and international students, depending on the scholarship type.


Applicants must meet Durham Universitys PhD admission requirements as outlined in the official application guidelines.


60th Anniversary Doctoral Excellence PhD Studentships


Open to both Home (UK) and International students.


Available for full-time PhD study at Durham University Business School, including the Department of Finance.


Applicants should consult the official application guidelines for detailed eligibility requirements.


DurhamChinese Scholarships Council (CSC) Studentships

Applicants must be citizens and permanent residents of the Peoples Republic of China at the time of application.


These scholarships are available across all disciplines, including Finance.

Research Environment: Vibrant, collaborative, and research-intensive

Stipend: 20,780 per year

Full payment of tuition fees


Annual stipend


Return airfare


Medical expenses

For the DurhamCSC Studentships, applicants must submit their PhD application via the Postgraduate Applicant Portal before the stated deadline.

Her Africa Early-Stage Incubator (HAESI) 2026 Cohort: the Alliance for Women and Girls (AFWAG)

Across Africa, young leaders are driving transformative change in gender justice, womens empowerment, and community development. Yet, many of these innovators face significant challenges: limited access to networks, scarce resources, and insufficient systems to scale their impact. Recognizing these barriers, the Alliance for Women and Girls (AFWAG) has launched the Her Africa Early-Stage Incubator (HAESI), a fully funded program designed to support founders under the age of 35 who are building solutions for women and girls.
The 2026 cohort of HAESI is now open for applications, offering a unique opportunity for early-stage leaders to strengthen their initiatives, expand their reach, and influence broader societal norms and policies.

What HAESI Offers
The Her Africa Early-Stage Incubator is not just a training programit is a comprehensive leadership journey that equips participants with tools, networks, and practices to sustain long-term impact. The 2026 cohort will provide:

Six-Month Leadership Journey Participants will engage in a structured program that emphasizes personal growth, organizational development, and strategic leadership. This journey is designed to help founders refine their vision, strengthen their management skills, and build resilience in the face of challenges.
Pan-African Houses & Peer Exchange Collaboration lies at the heart of HAESI. Founders will join Pan-African Houses, fostering peer-to-peer learning and cross-cultural exchange. These networks encourage participants to share experiences, learn from diverse contexts, and co-create solutions that resonate across the continent.
Systems-Level Tools Beyond project management, HAESI equips leaders with systems-level approaches to tackle structural barriers. This includes frameworks for influencing policy, shifting narratives, and embedding gender justice into broader social and economic systems.
Community Care and Liberatory Practice Recognizing the importance of wellbeing, the incubator integrates practices of community care and liberation. Participants are encouraged to prioritize mental health, collective healing, and sustainable activism, ensuring that their leadership is both impactful and enduring.
Networks That Last Beyond the Programme One of HAESIs most valuable offerings is its enduring network. Alumni remain connected through ongoing collaborations, mentorship opportunities, and shared advocacy efforts, creating a Pan-African community of gender justice leaders.


Why HAESI Matters
For many early-stage founders, the journey of building solutions for women and girls can be isolating. Without access to supportive ecosystems, promising initiatives risk stagnation or collapse. HAESI addresses this gap by providing a platform where leaders can thrive collectively.
The incubator is particularly significant because it goes beyond supporting individual projects. Its focus on influencing norms, narratives, and policy ensures that participants are equipped to drive systemic change. This approach recognizes that gender justice is not achieved through isolated interventions but through sustained efforts that reshape societal structures.

Eligibility and Application
The 2026 cohort is open to founders under 35 years old who are actively building solutions for women and girls in Africa. Applicants should demonstrate a commitment to gender justice and a readiness to engage in a six-month leadership journey.
Applications are currently being accepted through the official HAESI portal. Interested candidates are encouraged to apply promptly to secure their place in this transformative program.

The Her Africa Early-Stage Incubator represents a bold step toward nurturing the next generation of gender justice leaders in Africa. By offering a fully funded, six-month program that combines leadership development, peer exchange, systems-level tools, and community care, HAESI empowers young founders to scale their impact and influence societal transformation.
For early-stage leaders under 35, this is an invitation to join a Pan-African movement dedicated to advancing the rights and wellbeing of women and girls. Apply now and become part of a community that is reshaping Africas future.
